<figure>
    <img src="https://cdni.rt.com/files/2021.12/article/61a76e7685f5400dad299c98.JPG">
    <figcaption>Steam rises from the chimneys of a thermal power plant behind the Ivan the Great Bell Tower in Moscow, Russia. / <span class="copyright">Maxim Shemetov</span> / <span class="copyright">Reuters</span></figcaption></figure>
        
        <h1>World Bank offers its green guidance to Russia</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T12:49:14+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 12:49</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>The World Bank (WB) has suggested Russia introduce a carbon tax in industries with high greenhouse gas emissions, including the fuel and energy sector, to reach carbon neutrality goals.</strong></p>
    <p>&ldquo;<em>Putting a price on carbon is the bedrock for the broader range of climate policy instruments. Carbon pricing can take a number of forms &ndash; usually as a tax or a tradeable permit system</em>,&rdquo; the WB said in its report on the Russian economy published on Wednesday.</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/russia/541787-plan-green-energy-superpower/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>It specified that &ldquo;<em>making polluters pay for the prevention of costs they impose on society</em>&rdquo; would help gain resources that can be used to accelerate Russia&rsquo;s green transition.</p>
<p>&ldquo;<em>Energy, transport and major industrial plants are some of the most common sectors to have carbon pricing applied... Including these emissions in carbon pricing would cover 79% of emissions in Russia</em>,&rdquo; the report noted.</p>
<p>While the organization suggests Russia focus on carbon pricing by setting a tax or a fee-based permit system, it also mentions alternatives such as a greenhouse gas emissions trading system (GHG). This is based on the &lsquo;cap and trade&rsquo; system, in which the authorities set an aggregate emission limit for a number of polluting sites, which is then divided into quotas and distributed among them. Another alternative is introducing emissions-based energy taxes, or energy excise taxes, which, the WB notes, are currently very low in Russia by international standards.</p>
<p>In August, Moscow announced it would set up a number of working groups to oversee the country&rsquo;s transition to green energy, with a focus on renewables and environmental protection, and a target of reaching carbon neutrality by 2060. Despite coming under fire for setting a target so far off &ndash; a decade after many other nations &ndash; Russian President Vladimir Putin insisted that the country is doing its part to reduce emissions.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.rt.com/russia/538484-global-energy-transition-russia/"><strong>READ MORE:&nbsp;Russia to spend $1.3 trillion on transition to environmentally friendly energy sources over 28 years &ndash; Deputy PM ahead of COP26</strong></a></p>

<p>The WB report stresses, however, that in order to achieve this goal, Russian authorities must &ldquo;take concrete actions of moving towards decarbonization&rdquo; in the nearest future.</p>
