        <h1>Beijing slams Australia over ‘delusional miscalculation’</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T12:20:27+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 12:20</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>China has called out Australian Defense Minister Peter Dutton over an “irresponsible” assessment of its foreign policy, after a speech in which he questioned if a potential takeover of Taiwan would be enough to “satisfy” Beijing.</strong></p>
    <p>During a press conference on Tuesday, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhao Lijian specifically referred to Dutton&rsquo;s <em>&ldquo;irresponsible&rdquo;</em> remarks and criticized him for <em>&ldquo;brazenly [distorting]&rdquo;</em> China&rsquo;s efforts to <em>&ldquo;safeguard national sovereignty and territorial integrity.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>In his address at Canberra&rsquo;s National Press Club on Friday, Dutton had warned that the current strategic atmosphere in the region had <em>&ldquo;echoes of the 1930s&rdquo;</em> &ndash; seemingly referring to the tensions ahead of WWII.</p>
<p>Claiming that Beijing viewed other nations in the area as <em>&ldquo;tributary states,&rdquo;</em> he suggested that Taiwan &ndash; which China has long claimed as part of its territory &ndash; would only be the first domino to fall. He raised the specter of a potential Chinese takeover of the Senkaku Islands, which are the focus of a territorial dispute with Japan.</p>
<p>Referencing the speech, described as <em>&ldquo;hawkish&rdquo;</em> by the media, Zhao accused Dutton of <em>&ldquo;[misleading] the Australian people on the regional situation and priorities&rdquo;</em> and <em>&ldquo;[inciting] conflict and division between countries and peoples.&rdquo;</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p><em><strong>The remarks run counter to the trend of peace, development, and co-operation in our world today and are detrimental to regional peace and stability.</strong></em></p>
</blockquote>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/news/541366-australia-china-spy-ship/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>Zhao criticized Dutton&rsquo;s <em>&ldquo;delusional miscalculation on China&rsquo;s foreign policy&rdquo;</em> and warned that <em>&ldquo;certain Australian politicians&rdquo;</em> should <em>&ldquo;stop hyping up the &lsquo;China threat&rsquo; narrative for selfish political gain.&rdquo;</em> He added that Australia was going down <em>&ldquo;the wrong path towards the point of no return.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>While Dutton maintained that the region was <em>&ldquo;not on an inevitable path to conflict,&rdquo;</em> he said a policy of <em>&ldquo;acquiescence or appeasement&rdquo;</em> was <em>&ldquo;worse.&rdquo;</em> He pledged to <em>&ldquo;do everything I can&rdquo;</em> to <em>&ldquo;deter [China] from a position of strength, not weakness&rdquo;</em> if Beijing <em>&ldquo;takes a path other than peace.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>In recent months, there have been rising tensions between the two countries due to a range of issues, including Taiwan, a bitter trade dispute over coal exports, and Canberra&rsquo;s trilateral AUKUS defense pact with the US and UK, which will see Australia obtain at least eight nuclear-powered submarines.</p>

