        <h1>Beijing is warned not to commit ‘economic suicide’</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T10:34:44+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 10:34</time>
        <time class="op-modified" dateTime="2021-12-01T10:37:20+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 10:37</time>    </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>Former Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe has warned China that the invasion of Taiwan would be “economic suicide,” noting that Japan and the US would not stand by and let it happen.</strong></p>
    <p>Speaking on Wednesday at a forum organized by Taiwanese think tank the Institute for National Policy Research, Abe said that an armed invasion of Taiwan would spell danger for Tokyo.&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>&ldquo;A Taiwan emergency is a Japanese emergency, and therefore an emergency for the Japan-US alliance. People in Beijing, President Xi Jinping in particular, should never have a misunderstanding in recognizing this,&rdquo;</em> he said.&nbsp;</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/news/541844-australia-covid19-center-break/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>The former prime minister added that Japan&rsquo;s Senkaku Islands, which China also claims, are a mere 100km (62 miles) or so away from Taiwan.</p>
<p>In a further warning to Beijing, Abe warned that Chinese adventurism could be the death knell for its economy. <em>&ldquo;A military adventure would be the path to economic suicide,&rdquo;</em> he said. <em>&ldquo;We must keep reiterating that peaceful ties between China and Taiwan are the only option.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>China responded on Wednesday, condemning Abe&rsquo;s remarks and registering its solemn representations through diplomatic channels at the comments made by the former Japanese leader.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Beijing claims Taiwan is an inalienable part of China, and it also has a long-running territorial dispute with Japan over the Senkaku Islands.</p>
