    <figcaption>Jens Stoltenberg speaks during a news conference after the first day of a meeting of the Alliance's foreign ministers in Riga, Latvia November 30, 2021 / <span class="copyright">Ints Kalnins</span> / <span class="copyright">Reuters</span></figcaption></figure>
        
        <h1>NATO provides guarantees to allies & not partners like Ukraine – Stoltenberg</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T08:46:56+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 08:46</time>
        <time class="op-modified" dateTime="2021-12-01T10:29:26+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 10:29</time>    </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>Ukraine is not a member of NATO, and therefore the US-led bloc cannot guarantee that it would fight on its behalf in case of Russian military "aggression," its Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg said on Tuesday.</strong></p>
    <p>Speaking at a press conference in Latvia, where he is visiting for a meeting of NATO foreign ministers, the former Norwegian prime minister emphasized that Ukraine is just a partner and the terms of the bloc&rsquo;s agreement state that it goes to war to defend its own members.</p>
<p><em>&ldquo;We must understand the difference between a NATO ally, for example, Latvia, Poland, and Romania, and a close and highly valued partner [such as] Ukraine, for which we provide support, training capacity, equipment,&rdquo;</em> he explained, pointing out that there is no obligation for the bloc to protect Kiev.</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/russia/541778-nato-shipping-weaponry-border/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>Stoltenberg&rsquo;s comments come amid increasing fears over alleged military buildup on the Russia-Ukraine border. Suggestions of a possible armed conflict have been pushed by a number of Western media outlets, including America&rsquo;s CBS News, which reported that a military incursion is increasing in likelihood <em>&ldquo;as the weather gets colder.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>Earlier this month, Stoltenberg suggested that Moscow had arranged a <em>&ldquo;large and unusual concentration&rdquo;</em> of troops and equipment near the frontier, and warned that <em>&ldquo;any further provocation or aggressive actions&rdquo;</em> would be of serious concern.</p>
<p>All suggestions that Russia wants to invade Ukraine have been denied by the Kremlin, which has consistently stated that troop movements within Russian borders are no business of foreign countries.</p>
<p><em>&ldquo;The very allegations that Russia is going to attack someone, and accusations that Russia is somehow being aggressive, are completely groundless,&rdquo;</em> said Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov on Monday.</p>

