    <meta property="fb:op-recirculation-ads" content="placement_id=131217400945872_131237100943902">
</head>
<body>
<article>
    <header>
                    
<figure>
    <img src="https://cdni.rt.com/files/2021.11/article/61a64c102030275d3e7cc9a6.jpg">
    <figcaption>FILE PHOTO © AFP / Robyn Beck</figcaption></figure>
        
        <h1>French say ‘non merci’ to nonbinary pronouns</h1>

        <address><a>Helen Buyniski</a></address>        <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T08:12:36+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 08:12</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>France is choking on ‘le wokisme,’ as speakers of the New Normal’s argot struggle to convert their fellows – forcing them through linguistic hoops that are not compatible with French language or culture.</strong></p>
    <p>French First Lady Brigitte Macron has affirmed the language has &ldquo;<em>two pronouns: he and she</em>&rdquo; (<em>il</em> and <em>elle</em>, en Fran&ccedil;ais).&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<em>Our language is beautiful. And two pronouns are appropriate</em>,&rdquo; she declared succinctly earlier this month.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/news/541770-france-zemmour-macron-president/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>Such seemingly-innocuous words have France&rsquo;s would-be woke activists up in arms, accusing the centrist government of &ldquo;<em>violence</em>.&rdquo; Non-binary student Lilian Delhomme told the New York Times the expression &ldquo;<em>made [them] lose hope</em>,&rdquo; suggesting the age difference between the Macrons should have changed the first lady&rsquo;s perspective on social norms.&nbsp;</p>
<p>But, like the distaste many native Spanish speakers feel toward &ldquo;<em>Latinx</em>&rdquo; &ndash; the genderless stand-in meant to delineate a Latino or Latina individual by woke (usually white) organizers in an effort to appear inclusive &ndash; most French-speakers find it at the very least unpleasant to attempt to communicate without gender.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Their language is structured based upon it. There&rsquo;s no getting around the masculine and feminine nouns that describe every object &ndash; not that the wannabe-woke among the French haven&rsquo;t tried it.&nbsp;</p>
<p>A movement for so-called &ldquo;<em>inclusive writing</em>&rdquo; has butted heads with France&rsquo;s famously conservative Acad&eacute;mie fran&ccedil;aise, which described any changes put forth by the would-be reformers as &ldquo;<em>harmful to the practice and intelligibility of the French language.</em>&rdquo;</p>
<p>That hasn&rsquo;t stopped a small but determined contingent from attempting to adopt a genderless pronoun, importing &ldquo;<em>le wokisme</em>&rdquo; from the US with the neologism &ldquo;<em>iel&rdquo;</em>&nbsp;(a mixture between the masculine &ldquo;<em>il</em>&rdquo; and the feminine &ldquo;<em>elle</em>&rdquo;).</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s not going so well for iel, though. Center-right legislator Fran&ccedil;ois Jolivet has spearheaded a campaign to keep the gender-neutral pronoun out of Le Petit Robert dictionary, declaring its inclusion to be a form of &ldquo;<em>militancy</em>&rdquo; &ndash; &ldquo;<em>you legitimize words, you legitimize thoughts</em>,&rdquo; he said, describing himself in an interview with the French press as &ldquo;<em>a tolerant man convinced that &lsquo;iel&rsquo; was the wrong battle</em>.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/news/541727-france-britain-channel-crossings-row/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>Even left-wing outlet Lib&eacute;ration seems to not be entertaining the genderless American way, one headline snarkily describing &ldquo;<em>The Highway to Iel</em>.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The linguistic conservatism of the French is protected not only by the Academie fran&ccedil;aise&rsquo;s staunch opposition to what one member recently termed &ldquo;<em>brainless Globish</em>,&rdquo; but by a hard-coded avoidance of racial politics &ndash; the country is legally prohibited from compiling racial statistics, making it nearly impossible for le wokisme to find a foothold.</p>
<p>But &ldquo;<em>iel</em>&rdquo; made it into Le Petit Robert &ndash; the online edition, at least &ndash; upsetting education minister Jean-Michel Blanquer, who accused the publisher of &ldquo;<em>manipulat[ing] the French language</em>.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<em>Iel</em>,&rdquo; he said, was a clear expression of &ldquo;<em>wokisme</em>.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s a subject he is familiar with, having blamed a backlash against American wokeness for the 2016 election of US President Donald Trump. Five years later, he has the French first lady on his side.</p>
<p>Indeed, the Macrons have proved to be a surprising ally for some. The French president &ndash; hardly a staunch conservative in the eyes of his supporters &ndash; might at first appear to be an easy convert to wokisme. Yet even he has bristled amid the onslaught of &lsquo;brainless Globish,&rsquo; deeming &ldquo;<em>certain social science theories entirely imported from the United States</em>&rdquo; as a potential threat to French culture.</p>
<p>However, Robert&rsquo;s managing director, Charles Bimbenet, echoed his American counterparts in defense of whatever &ldquo;<em>wokisme</em>&rdquo; might have found its way into his dictionary, insisting the reference book&rsquo;s mission was &ldquo;<em>to observe the evolution of a French language that is in motion and diverse, and take account of that</em>.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>As the Americans might say &ndash; and Macron might once have echoed &ndash; &ldquo;<em>diversity is our strength.</em>&rdquo;</p>

