        <h1>Left-wing wife of ousted Honduran leader wins presidential election</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T04:05:52+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 04:05</time>
        <time class="op-modified" dateTime="2021-12-01T05:55:33+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 05:55</time>    </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>Xiomara Castro, the wife of ousted former Honduran President Manuel Zelaya, was pronounced the winner of Honduras’ presidential election on Tuesday after rival Nasry Asfura conceded defeat.</strong></p>
    <p>Asfura conceded the election after 52% of the counted votes showed Castro had a clear majority of 53% over Asfura&rsquo;s 34% and he publicly <a href="https://news.yahoo.com/honduras-ruling-party-candidate-concedes-014401226.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">congratulated</a> her victory, saying, <em>&ldquo;I hope that God illuminates and guides her so that her administration does the best for the benefit of all of us Hondurans, to achieve development and the desires for democracy.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>US Secretary of State Antony Blinken also congratulated Castro for becoming Honduras&rsquo; first female president and said the US was looking forward to working with her government.</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/news/466687-zelaya-honduras-interview-coup/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p><em>&ldquo;We congratulate Hondurans for the high voter turnout, peaceful participation, and active civil society engagement that marked this election, signaling an enduring commitment to the democratic process,&rdquo;</em> Blinken declared.</p>
<p>Castro previously served as Honduras&rsquo; first lady between 2006 and 2009, up until her husband Manuel Zelaya was ousted in a military coup. Zelaya claimed the US was behind the coup and attributed it to his signing of Hugo Chavez&rsquo;s Bolivarian Alliance for the Peoples of Our America (ALBA).</p>
<p><em>&ldquo;The US warned me: If you sign the Bolivarian Alternative to the Americas (ALBA), you&rsquo;re going to have problems with the US. I signed it, and six months later, I had problems,&rdquo;</em> he told RT America in 2019, adding, <em>&ldquo;When you give them competition in the free market, they stop being capitalist. They become retrograde, authoritarian, and they play coups, wars, invasions.&rdquo;</em></p>

